---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SourceList from '../components/SourceList.astro';

// Culture & Heritage is a hand-built page: lived, material and artistic
// culture, distinct from the doctrinal topics under The Faith. Claims here are
// backed by the sources listed at the foot of the page.
const sources = [
  { title: 'Sikhism: A Very Short Introduction', author: 'Eleanor Nesbitt', publisher: 'Oxford University Press', year: 2005 },
  { title: 'The Sikhs: Their Religious Beliefs and Practices', author: 'W. Owen Cole and Piara Singh Sambhi', note: 'standard academic reference on Sikh belief and practice' },
  { title: 'A History of the Sikhs, Volume 1: 1469–1839', author: 'Khushwant Singh', publisher: 'Oxford University Press', year: 2004 },
  { title: 'Encyclopaedia Britannica — Sikhism', url: 'https://www.britannica.com/topic/Sikhism' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Culture & Heritage — Mission Sikhism"
  description="The lived culture of the Sikh world — its music, kitchens, language, art and global reach."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container culture">
      <h1>Culture &amp; Heritage</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Beyond belief and history lies a living culture — the sound, language,
        hospitality and craft through which Sikhi is practised day to day, in the
        Punjab and across a global diaspora.
      </p>

      <h2>The gurdwara and the langar</h2>
      <p>
        The <strong>gurdwara</strong> ("doorway to the Guru") is the Sikh place of
        worship, open to all regardless of faith or background. At its heart sits
        the Guru Granth Sahib, and attached to almost every gurdwara is the
        <strong>langar</strong> — the free community kitchen founded in Guru Nanak's
        own time, where volunteers cook and serve a meal to anyone who comes, all
        seated together on the floor as equals. Langar is Sikhi's most visible
        social teaching: equality and service made edible.
      </p>

      <h2>Sacred music</h2>
      <p>
        Sikh worship is sung. <strong>Kirtan</strong> — the singing of scripture —
        is central to Sikh devotional life, and the Guru Granth Sahib is itself
        organised by <em>raag</em>, the classical melodic framework to which each
        hymn is set. The tradition reaches back to Guru Nanak and his lifelong
        companion Bhai Mardana, who accompanied him on the rebab. Music remains the
        living voice of the scripture.
      </p>

      <h2>Language and script</h2>
      <p>
        Sikh scripture is written in <strong>Gurmukhi</strong>, the script
        standardised by Guru Angad, and its language is closely tied to Punjabi.
        Learning to read Gurmukhi is, for many Sikhs, a first step toward reading
        the Guru directly — and Punjabi language and literature are woven through
        Sikh cultural life.
      </p>

      <h2>Symbol and dress</h2>
      <p>
        The <strong>Nishan Sahib</strong>, the saffron triangular flag bearing the
        Khanda emblem, flies over every gurdwara. Initiated Sikhs keep the five
        articles of faith described under <a href="/faith/rehat-maryada">the Rehat
        Maryada</a>, of which the turban and uncut hair are the most recognised the
        world over — a visible commitment to identity and equality.
      </p>

      <h2>A martial tradition</h2>
      <p>
        From Guru Hargobind's doctrine of <em>miri-piri</em> onward, Sikhi has held
        together the spiritual and the martial. That heritage survives in the
        <strong>Akali Nihang</strong> orders and in <strong>gatka</strong>, the
        Sikh martial art demonstrated each year at
        <a href="/faith/festivals-and-gurpurabs">Hola Mohalla</a> in Anandpur.
      </p>

      <h2>A global community</h2>
      <p>
        Sikhs today live on every continent, carrying gurdwaras, langar and
        festival to cities far from the Punjab. The diaspora — shaped in part by
        the upheaval of <a href="/events/partition-of-punjab">Partition</a> and by
        later migration — has made Sikh culture a genuinely global presence while
        keeping its roots in the land of the Gurus.
      </p>

      <SourceList sources={sources} />

      <p class="muted-note">
        Draft for review — this page gives an overview; individual topics may be
        expanded into their own entries over time.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
